he error "temporary failure in name resolution" (often seen as ssh: Could not resolve hostname) indicates that your system cannot translate the server's hostname into an IP address.  This is a DNS (Domain Name System) issue, not necessarily an SSH problem. 

Meaning
The error means your system's DNS resolver is unable to contact a valid DNS server to look up the hostname you provided. Common causes include:

Incorrect DNS Configuration: The /etc/resolv.conf file lacks valid nameservers. 
Network Connectivity: No internet connection or the DNS server is unreachable. 
Firewall Blocking: Ports 53 (UDP/TCP) required for DNS queries are blocked. 
WSL Issues: On Windows Subsystem for Linux, the auto-generated DNS config may point to an unreachable internal proxy. 

