How to Fix (Linux/WSL)
1. Check and Update DNS Configuration
The most common fix is to manually specify a public DNS server. 

Open the configuration file:
sudo nano /etc/resolv.conf

Add or replace the nameserver lines with reliable public DNS IPs (e.g., Google or Cloudflare):
nameserver 8.8.8.8
nameserver 1.1.1.1

Save and exit (Ctrl+O, Enter, Ctrl+X).
Test: Try pinging a domain (ping google.com) or reconnecting via SSH. 
Note: If you are on WSL2, this file may reset on reboot.  To make it permanent, create/edit /etc/wsl.conf, add [network]\ngenerateResolvConf = false, save, then run wsl.exe --shutdown in Windows PowerShell before restarting WSL. 


